<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Atv.TestIdentity.targets

  Phase 03 (INFRA-16, "Test-time identity provisioning and deep isolation"): gives
  tests/Atv.AdapterTests its own per-worktree package identity, registered OUTSIDE the
  test run, and makes `dotnet test`'s normal exe launch actually carry that identity.

  ===================================================================================
  WHY THIS FILE IS NOT JUST A SECOND CONSUMER OF build/Atv.Package.targets
  ===================================================================================
  DIST-7 ("The release full-package manifest") settled, as a rule not to relitigate,
  that the src/release manifest template stamps exactly two fields: Identity Name and
  Version. The test pool needs a THIRD build-varying field - a per-worktree-unique
  AppExecutionAlias name - because, unlike the single dev-interactive pool, multiple
  worktrees' test pools must be able to register and run concurrently (INFRA-16's "two
  branches on one dev box run their real-API tests concurrently"): if every worktree's
  test manifest declared the same static alias, only the most-recently-registered
  worktree would actually own that alias's reparse-point stub, silently breaking every
  other worktree's suite. So this file stamps its OWN sibling template
  (tests/Atv.AdapterTests/Package/AppxManifest.template.xml) rather than importing
  Atv.Package.targets, keeping the src/release stamping rule fully untouched.

  ===================================================================================
  THE ONE OPEN MECHANIC (empirically settled 2026-07-08 on this machine, ARM64,
  Windows 11 26100, Developer Mode on) - direct launch does NOT carry identity;
  the AppExecutionAlias fallback DOES, via a filesystem-level trick:
  ===================================================================================
  Spike: with the existing dev-pool package already registered (loose layout,
  IsDevelopmentMode=True), directly launching its exe by full path
  (bin\...\AppX\atv.exe) returned NO package identity (Package.Current throws
  Arg_InvalidOperationException) - even though that exact file IS the manifest's
  declared Application/Executable, sitting inside the registered InstallLocation. But
  launching the SAME package's AppExecutionAlias stub
  (%LOCALAPPDATA%\Microsoft\WindowsApps\atv.exe, a reparse-point file the OS creates at
  registration time) DID carry identity - both via PATH and via its full path, and
  both via an inherited console (PowerShell `&`) and via System.Diagnostics.Process
  with RedirectStandardOutput/RedirectStandardError (i.e. exactly how
  Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild's InvokeTestingPlatformTask launches a test exe).
  So: identity comes specifically from CreateProcess-ing the ALIAS reparse-point file,
  not from merely residing inside (or being the declared Executable of) a registered
  package layout.

  A Windows hard link to that alias stub, created at an arbitrary OTHER path (proven:
  a repo-root file, a totally unrelated location), carries the SAME reparse tag -
  hard links share the underlying MFT record/reparse data - so launching a hard link
  to the alias stub ALSO carries identity, from anywhere. AtvEnsureTestIdentity below
  puts that hard link at the EXACT path $(TargetPath) normally occupies (the compiled
  apphost `dotnet test` launches) - not a side path it then has to redirect anything
  to. It first COPIES the freshly-built apphost from $(TargetPath) to a second,
  differently-named file (the name the AppxManifest's Application/Executable declares
  - see AtvStampTestManifest's stamped content), then deletes $(TargetPath) and
  re-creates it as the hard link. A plain copy of a .NET apphost works as a launcher
  for the same managed dll regardless of the copy's own filename or location -
  apphosts locate their managed entry-point assembly by a name baked into the binary
  at build time, not by their own current path - so the copy is a fully functional,
  independent launcher, while the original $(TargetPath) name becomes purely an
  identity-granting redirector.

  This is a pure filesystem trick, not a property-timing one, because empirically
  (2026-07-08) this repo's global.json ("test": {"runner": "Microsoft.Testing.Platform"})
  opt-in routes `dotnet test` through a DIFFERENT SDK-defined target,
  `_MTPBuild` (see Microsoft.Common.targets/ImportAfter/Microsoft.TestPlatform.ImportAfter.targets:
  `<Target Name="_MTPBuild"><MSBuild Projects="$(MSBuildProjectFullPath)" Condition="'$(IsTestingPlatformApplication)'=='true'" /></Target>`),
  never through Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild's own `_TestRunStart`/
  `InvokeTestingPlatform` targets at all - confirmed by their complete absence from a
  `dotnet test -v normal` log. `_MTPBuild` triggers a NESTED `<MSBuild>` build of the
  same project, then the `dotnet test` CLI itself launches the result, entirely outside
  any further MSBuild target - there is no guarantee it re-reads $(TargetPath) from the
  SAME evaluated project instance this file's targets could mutate, so a property
  reassignment (which is what would normally follow from "InvokeTestingPlatformTask
  reads $(TargetPath) as a task-parameter attribute right after `_TestRunStart`
  returns", the mechanism that DOES work for that older flow) cannot be relied on here.
  Swapping which FILE sits at the fixed, well-known $(TargetPath) has no such
  timing/re-evaluation hazard: whichever flow, and whenever `dotnet test` (or a human,
  or VS Test Explorer) ends up launching that path, it gets whatever is on disk there
  at that moment. Both `_TestRunStart` and `_MTPBuild` are therefore wired as hooks onto
  the SAME AtvEnsureTestIdentity target below, covering either execution model.

  This keeps the in-test gate (IdentityGate.cs) honest to INFRA-16's letter: it still
  ONLY asserts (checks GetCurrentPackageFullName) and SKIPS on absence - by the time
  Main() runs, the process already has identity or it doesn't, entirely as a
  consequence of what got CreateProcess-ed before the managed code ever started. The
  gate never registers, and never relaunches, in-proc.

  ===================================================================================
  TARGETS IN THIS FILE
  ===================================================================================
  AtvStampTestManifest    - stamps Package/AppxManifest.template.xml with this
                             worktree's Identity Name / Version / Alias, writes the
                             result straight into $(TargetDir) (this pool has no
                             release-pack reuse concern, so unlike DIST-7's obj/ copy
                             there is no separate "stamp to obj, consume out-of-process"
                             step - the stamped manifest just needs to sit next to the
                             exe/assets it describes so the whole folder is one
                             self-consistent loose-layout package root).
  AtvBuildTestIdentityTool - builds tools/Atv.TestIdentityTool and resolves its exe
                             path, for every target below that shells out to it.
  AtvEnsureTestIdentity    - the register-or-assert hook, wired onto BOTH
                             `_TestRunStart` and `_MTPBuild` (see above): register +
                             copy-the-apphost-aside + hard-link $(TargetPath) to the
                             alias stub, all OUTSIDE the test process itself. Runs on
                             every `dotnet test` invocation - never on a plain
                             `dotnet run`/`dotnet build` of this project (neither hook
                             target is ever invoked by those), which is exactly why a
                             direct exe launch in a fresh worktree (neither hook has
                             ever fired) still gets the documented SKIP
                             (IdentityGate.cs) rather than identity it was never
                             granted.
  AtvTestRegister          - explicit, standalone "Register" (same register step,
                             invokable without running tests: `dotnet build
                             tests\Atv.AdapterTests\Atv.AdapterTests.csproj
                             -t:AtvTestRegister`).
  AtvTestUnregister        - explicit "Unregister": removes THIS worktree's test
                             identity. Never invoked automatically (INFRA-16:
                             unregistering out from under the running identity-holding
                             process kills it mid-run; registration persists between
                             runs by design).
  AtvTestSweepOrphans      - explicit "SweepOrphans": removes every registered
                             `<brand>.Test.*` identity (any worktree, not just this
                             one) whose InstallLocation no longer exists on disk -
                             crashed runs, deleted worktrees. Spares this worktree's
                             own live registration even though its Name also matches
                             the prefix.
  All four Exec-based targets shell out to tools/Atv.TestIdentityTool, a tiny separate
  console exe, because MSBuild has no built-in way to await a WinRT
  IAsyncOperationWithProgress - see that project's own file-header comment for the
  fuller rationale (also: it must run as a SEPARATE PROCESS from the test host anyway,
  per INFRA-16's "outside the test run" / "external, non-identity step" rules).
-->
<Project xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/developer/msbuild/2003">

  <PropertyGroup>
    <_AtvTestManifestTemplate>$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)\Package\AppxManifest.template.xml</_AtvTestManifestTemplate>

    <!--
      Worktree-derived identifiers. Deliberately evaluation-time (not inside a
      target): none of these depend on NBGV's $(BuildVersion) or on
      $(IntermediateOutputPath)'s RID segment the way DIST-7's stamp does, so there is
      no equivalent hazard to the one Atv.Package.targets guards against.

      Same hash mechanism as Atv.Package.targets ($(MSBuildProjectDirectory) of the
      IMPORTING project, i.e. tests/Atv.AdapterTests here) - so two worktrees
      necessarily hash differently (AC3's isolation property), and this pool's own
      project directory differs from src/Atv's, so even within one worktree the test
      pool and the dev pool never collide.
    -->
    <_AtvTestPathHash>$([MSBuild]::StableStringHash('$(MSBuildProjectDirectory)').ToString("x8"))</_AtvTestPathHash>
    <!-- "<brand>.Test.<hash>" - recognizable by the AtvTestSweepOrphans prefix check (AC5) as belonging to the test pool, not the dev/release pools ("<brand>-<hash>", a different separator, from Atv.Package.targets). -->
    <_AtvTestIdentityName>$(AtvBrandName).Test.$(_AtvTestPathHash)</_AtvTestIdentityName>
    <!-- Alias attribute values must be a bare file name ending ".exe"; derived from the command constant, not re-literaled (standing invariant #2/#3). -->
    <_AtvTestAlias>$(AtvCommandName)-test-$(_AtvTestPathHash).exe</_AtvTestAlias>

    <_AtvTestIdentityToolProject>$(MSBuildThisFileDirectory)..\tools\Atv.TestIdentityTool\Atv.TestIdentityTool.csproj</_AtvTestIdentityToolProject>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <!-- Every action target below depends (transitively) on this - $(AtvBrandName)/$(AtvCommandName) feed the worktree-derived identifiers computed in the PropertyGroup above. -->
  <Target Name="AtvValidateTestIdentityInputs">
    <Error Condition="'$(AtvBrandName)' == ''"
           Text="[Atv.TestIdentity] AtvBrandName is empty - brand extraction from src/Atv/Branding.cs (Directory.Build.props) failed." />
    <Error Condition="'$(AtvCommandName)' == ''"
           Text="[Atv.TestIdentity] AtvCommandName is empty - brand extraction from src/Atv/Branding.cs (Directory.Build.props) failed." />
  </Target>

  <Target Name="AtvStampTestManifest" DependsOnTargets="AtvValidateTestIdentityInputs;Build;GetBuildVersion">
    <Error Condition="!Exists('$(_AtvTestManifestTemplate)')"
           Text="[Atv.TestIdentity] AppxManifest template not found at '$(_AtvTestManifestTemplate)'." />

    <PropertyGroup>
      <!--
        Straight into $(TargetDir) (bin\, not obj\): this manifest's only consumer is
        the register step below, which needs one self-consistent folder containing the
        manifest AND the exe/assets it describes - there is no RID-qualified
        release-pack reuse of this particular template (that is what DIST-7's own
        src template still handles for phase 12).
      -->
      <_AtvTestStampedManifestPath>$(TargetDir)AppxManifest.xml</_AtvTestStampedManifestPath>
      <_AtvTestTemplateContent>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('$(_AtvTestManifestTemplate)'))</_AtvTestTemplateContent>
      <_AtvTestStampedContent>$(_AtvTestTemplateContent.Replace('{IdentityName}', '$(_AtvTestIdentityName)').Replace('{Version}', '$(BuildVersion)').Replace('{Alias}', '$(_AtvTestAlias)'))</_AtvTestStampedContent>
    </PropertyGroup>

    <MakeDir Directories="$(TargetDir)" Condition="!Exists('$(TargetDir)')" />

    <WriteLinesToFile
        File="$(_AtvTestStampedManifestPath)"
        Lines="$(_AtvTestStampedContent)"
        Overwrite="true"
        WriteOnlyWhenDifferent="true" />

    <Message Importance="high"
             Text="[Atv.TestIdentity] Stamped manifest: $(_AtvTestStampedManifestPath) (Identity Name=$(_AtvTestIdentityName), Alias=$(_AtvTestAlias), Version=$(BuildVersion))" />
  </Target>

  <Target Name="AtvBuildTestIdentityTool" DependsOnTargets="AtvValidateTestIdentityInputs">
    <MSBuild Projects="$(_AtvTestIdentityToolProject)" Targets="Build" Properties="Configuration=$(Configuration)" />
    <!-- GetTargetPath returns the managed .dll (the actual "target" of a build), never
         the native apphost .exe - CreateProcess-ing a bare .dll directly doesn't run
         it as a program, it fails to resolve the runtime. ChangeExtension to get the
         apphost this tool is invoked as. -->
    <MSBuild Projects="$(_AtvTestIdentityToolProject)" Targets="GetTargetPath" Properties="Configuration=$(Configuration)">
      <Output TaskParameter="TargetOutputs" PropertyName="_AtvTestIdentityToolDll" />
    </MSBuild>
    <PropertyGroup>
      <_AtvTestIdentityToolExe>$([System.IO.Path]::ChangeExtension('$(_AtvTestIdentityToolDll)', '.exe'))</_AtvTestIdentityToolExe>
    </PropertyGroup>
  </Target>

  <!--
    The register-or-assert hook. Two BeforeTargets/AfterTargets hooks point at the SAME
    target because two different `dotnet test` execution models exist across SDK
    versions/configurations, and this file has no reliable way to know which one a
    given invocation will use:
      - `_TestRunStart` (Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild's own extension point,
        called from its InvokeTestingPlatform target) - fires when TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport-style
        VSTest-shim integration is in play.
      - `_MTPBuild` (a plain SDK-defined target - see
        $(MSBuildExtensionsPath)\..\Current\Microsoft.Common.targets\ImportAfter\Microsoft.TestPlatform.ImportAfter.targets -
        `<Target Name="_MTPBuild"><MSBuild Projects="$(MSBuildProjectFullPath)" Condition="'$(IsTestingPlatformApplication)'=='true'" /></Target>`)
        is what this repo's global.json `"test": {"runner": "Microsoft.Testing.Platform"}`
        opt-in actually drives `dotnet test` through (verified empirically 2026-07-08: with
        that global.json setting, `_TestRunStart` never fires at all - `_MTPBuild` does a
        NESTED Build and the `dotnet test` CLI launches the exe itself afterward, entirely
        outside any further MSBuild target). Crucially, `_MTPBuild` is ONLY ever invoked by
        `dotnet test`'s own orchestration, never by a plain `dotnet build`/`dotnet run` of
        this project - so AfterTargets="_MTPBuild" is just as much a "fires on run, not
        build" signal as `_TestRunStart` was meant to be.

    Given that uncertainty, this hook does NOT rely on reassigning the MSBuild
    $(TargetPath) property (the approach that works for the `_TestRunStart` flow, since
    InvokeTestingPlatformTask reads it as a task-parameter attribute in the SAME target
    execution right after) - there is no guarantee the native `dotnet test` CLI re-reads
    $(TargetPath) from the SAME evaluated project instance this target mutated; it may
    re-evaluate the project fresh to decide what to launch, in which case a property
    mutation here would silently never be seen.

    Instead this is a pure FILESYSTEM trick, robust regardless of when/how many times
    $(TargetPath) gets re-read: after Build, the compiled apphost (NOT $(TargetPath)
    itself - that is always the managed .dll, even for a UseAppHost=true Exe project;
    the apphost sits alongside it at the same name with a ".exe" extension, see
    AtvEnsureTestIdentity's own remarks) is COPIED to a second, differently-named file
    ($(_AtvTestRealExePath), e.g. ...\Atv.AdapterTests.real.exe - the name the
    manifest's Application/Executable declares) - a plain byte-for-byte copy works as a
    launcher for the same managed dll because a .NET apphost locates its managed
    entry-point dll by a name baked into the apphost binary itself at publish time, not by
    the apphost file's own current name (proven empirically: renaming/copying an apphost
    exe to an arbitrary name and running it from the AppExecutionAlias hardlink already
    relies on exactly this property). The apphost's ORIGINAL path is then DELETED and
    re-created as a hard link to the freshly-registered AppExecutionAlias stub. Whatever
    later launches that fixed apphost path - from this same execution or a completely
    fresh one - gets the SAME path either way; only the FILE sitting there changed, so
    there is no property-visibility race to worry about.

    This keeps the in-test gate (IdentityGate.cs) honest to INFRA-16's letter: it still
    ONLY asserts (checks GetCurrentPackageFullName) and SKIPS on absence - by the time
    Main() runs, the process already has identity or it doesn't, entirely as a
    consequence of what got CreateProcess-ed before the managed code ever started. The
    gate never registers, and never relaunches, in-proc.
  -->
  <Target Name="AtvEnsureTestIdentity" BeforeTargets="_TestRunStart" AfterTargets="_MTPBuild" DependsOnTargets="AtvStampTestManifest;AtvBuildTestIdentityTool">
    <Exec Command="&quot;$(_AtvTestIdentityToolExe)&quot; register &quot;$(_AtvTestStampedManifestPath)&quot; &quot;$(_AtvTestIdentityName)&quot;" />

    <PropertyGroup>
      <_AtvTestAliasStubPath>$(LOCALAPPDATA)\Microsoft\WindowsApps\$(_AtvTestAlias)</_AtvTestAliasStubPath>
      <!--
        $(TargetPath) is the MANAGED assembly (the .dll - true for every SDK-style
        project, Exe-typed or not; confirmed empirically via AtvBuildTestIdentityTool's
        own GetTargetPath call needing the same ChangeExtension). The native apphost
        .exe this project's own Build already produces (UseAppHost defaults true for a
        Windows Exe project) sits alongside it at the same name with a ".exe"
        extension - THAT is the file that must become the hard link (identity is
        granted to the launched PROCESS, and dotnet test launches the apphost, not the
        managed dll directly). Hard-linking $(TargetPath) itself the first time this
        was tried replaced the .dll with the (non-loadable) alias-stub reparse point
        and broke every subsequent run with a FileLoadException - do not repeat that.
      -->
      <_AtvTestApphostPath>$([System.IO.Path]::ChangeExtension('$(TargetPath)', '.exe'))</_AtvTestApphostPath>
      <!-- Must match the AppxManifest template's static Application/Executable value. -->
      <_AtvTestRealExePath>$(TargetDir)Atv.AdapterTests.real.exe</_AtvTestRealExePath>
    </PropertyGroup>

    <Error Condition="!Exists('$(_AtvTestAliasStubPath)')"
           Text="[Atv.TestIdentity] Register reported success but the AppExecutionAlias stub was not found at '$(_AtvTestAliasStubPath)'. Is Developer Mode on (Settings > Privacy &amp; security > For developers)?" />
    <Error Condition="!Exists('$(_AtvTestApphostPath)')"
           Text="[Atv.TestIdentity] Expected the compiled apphost at '$(_AtvTestApphostPath)' - is UseAppHost disabled for this project?" />

    <!-- Idempotent every time: Build may have just rewritten the apphost with fresh compiled output, so both the copy and the hard link are redone unconditionally on every AtvEnsureTestIdentity run. -->
    <Copy SourceFiles="$(_AtvTestApphostPath)" DestinationFiles="$(_AtvTestRealExePath)" />
    <Delete Files="$(_AtvTestApphostPath)" />
    <Exec Command="cmd.exe /c mklink /H &quot;$(_AtvTestApphostPath)&quot; &quot;$(_AtvTestAliasStubPath)&quot;" />
  </Target>

  <!-- Explicit "Register": the exact same register + copy + hard-link steps, standalone-invokable, never required for tests to pass (AC5). -->
  <Target Name="AtvTestRegister" DependsOnTargets="AtvEnsureTestIdentity" />

  <!--
    Explicit "Unregister": removes this worktree's own test identity. External,
    non-identity step - never wired to any automatic hook.

    Also restores $(TargetPath)'s apphost from the AtvEnsureTestIdentity-saved copy,
    if the two have diverged (i.e. $(TargetPath) is currently the hard link, not a
    real apphost) - otherwise a direct exe launch right after an explicit unregister
    finds a now-DANGLING hard link (its target, the alias stub, was just removed) and
    fails to start at all ("the file cannot be accessed by the system"), instead of
    IdentityGate's clean, documented SKIP (AC2's actual concern: a launch with no
    identity should skip gracefully, never crash). The very next `dotnet test` repairs
    this regardless (AtvEnsureTestIdentity always redoes the copy+link unconditionally,
    which is what AC5 relies on), but restoring it here too keeps this target's own
    side effects self-contained.
  -->
  <Target Name="AtvTestUnregister" DependsOnTargets="AtvBuildTestIdentityTool">
    <Exec Command="&quot;$(_AtvTestIdentityToolExe)&quot; unregister &quot;$(_AtvTestIdentityName)&quot;" />

    <PropertyGroup>
      <_AtvTestApphostPath>$([System.IO.Path]::ChangeExtension('$(TargetPath)', '.exe'))</_AtvTestApphostPath>
      <_AtvTestRealExePath>$(TargetDir)Atv.AdapterTests.real.exe</_AtvTestRealExePath>
    </PropertyGroup>
    <Delete Files="$(_AtvTestApphostPath)" Condition="Exists('$(_AtvTestRealExePath)') And Exists('$(_AtvTestApphostPath)')" />
    <Copy SourceFiles="$(_AtvTestRealExePath)" DestinationFiles="$(_AtvTestApphostPath)"
          Condition="Exists('$(_AtvTestRealExePath)') And !Exists('$(_AtvTestApphostPath)')" />
  </Target>

  <!-- Explicit "SweepOrphans": reaps orphaned "<brand>.Test.*" registrations (any worktree) whose install location no longer exists. Spares this worktree's own live one. -->
  <Target Name="AtvTestSweepOrphans" DependsOnTargets="AtvBuildTestIdentityTool">
    <PropertyGroup>
      <_AtvTestBrandTestPrefix>$(AtvBrandName).Test</_AtvTestBrandTestPrefix>
    </PropertyGroup>
    <Exec Command="&quot;$(_AtvTestIdentityToolExe)&quot; sweep &quot;$(_AtvTestBrandTestPrefix)&quot; &quot;$(TargetDir)&quot;" />
  </Target>

</Project>
